{"key":"processedPost-9713317","value":{"id":9713317,"first":9711812,"last":9716272,"when":1233450015,"utime":"02/01/09 03:00 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>muse said:</strong><br />I thought misting pins was bad, that it might cause aborts.&nbsp; I'm almost certain I have read this many times in these forums. </blockquote><br />You have read that.<br />It's because several years ago, the knowledge of the mushroom growing life cycle was not as evolved as it is now.&nbsp; That bad advice was circulating when people thought that the best way to build a terrarium was to seal it up tight.&nbsp; If you have an air-tight terrarium, and you mist, there's nowhere for that moisture to go, so the pins drown.&nbsp; If you're providing the proper amount of fresh air, your pins will benefit from misting, and in fact they require it.<br />Since air exchange is the number 1 pinning trigger, you MUST mist or your substrate will dry out.&nbsp; It's amazing how many new growers build a perfectly good fruiting chamber, and then bitch that it won't 'maintain humidity'.&nbsp; When prodded for information, the story comes out that they're not misting. <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif\" alt=\":shrug:\" title=\":shrug:\"/><br />RR","title":"Re: misting"}}